## Workflow Example

```
1. Create stream for feature work
   tracker.createStream({ name: 'auth-feature', agentId: 'manager' })
   → stream/abc123 created

2. Create tasks for the stream
   tracker.createTask({ title: 'Implement login', streamId: 'abc123' })
   tracker.createTask({ title: 'Implement logout', streamId: 'abc123' })

3. Agent starts a task
   tracker.startTask({ taskId: 'wt-xyz', agentId: 'worker-1', worktree })
   → Creates worker/worker-1/wt-xyz@timestamp from stream HEAD

4. Agent makes commits on worker branch
   (normal git workflow in worktree)

5. Agent completes task
   tracker.completeTask({ taskId: 'wt-xyz', worktree })
   → Merges worker branch to stream with --no-ff
   → Full commit history preserved

6. Create diff stack for review
   tracker.createStackFromStream({ streamId: 'abc123', name: 'Auth PR' })
   → Checkpoints created from stream commits

7. After review approval, cherry-pick to main
   tracker.cherryPickStackToTarget(stackId, worktree)
   → Commits landed on main
```

## What Changes from Current Model

| Current | New |
|---------|-----|
| All branches are streams (heavy tracking) | Streams + lightweight worker tasks |
| Automatic cascade rebase | User-initiated sync only |
| Change-Id on all commits | Change-Id optional (only for review) |
| Stream status drives everything | Task status for workers, stream status for integration |

## What Stays the Same

- Stream creation, forking, merging APIs (unchanged)
- Worktree management per agent
- Operations audit trail (for streams)
- Diff stacks for review
- Merge queue for landing
- Conflict handling (on streams)

